metadata.name: Colored Elementary Cellular Automaton #38
metadata.description:
The algorithm is based on Stephen Wolfram's Elementary Cellular Automaton. 
This is a 1D cellular automaton with a neighborhood of 5 cells. This gives us 2^5 = 32 patterns for a neighborhood and 2^32 = 4.29B possible combinations!!! The size of the cell varies in a range of 2 to 8. There is a 15% of getting a black and white art.

Pattern rarity:
- Pattern 1 _25%
- Pattern 2 _30%
- Pattern 3 _35%
- Pattern 4 _15%

Note: The art might look in different resolutions because of the responsive view, but the color, pattern, and layout remain the same.

metadata.name: Celebration in Times of Measure #286
metadata.description:
Intentionally developed by placing constraints on the process.

Everything is generated by code written in P5js.

Press '1' for the default, textured version
Press '2' to add outlines and see the form structure

Press '3' to see a flat, untextured version
Press '4' to add outlines (flat version)

Press 'e' to end/skip the initial animation
Press 'r' to restart/replay the animation
Press 's' to save current image (in live view)

Created by Walter Anderson (@noxiarb)

metadata.name: operation 04 #116
metadata.description:
The final extrapolation of the operation Voronoi series. Multiple walk sequences are added, as is another drawing method, for increased variety. Five traits describe each mint: 

Color: Ten different named color palettes, with "Monochrome" the rarest.

Arcs: The number of elements drawn, with 100 the rarest.

Resolution: The X/Y resolution of Voronoi nodes, with 2 the rarest.

Pattern: The walk style, with "Static" being the rarest.

Shape: The drawing element, either ellipse or, someone less likely, rectangle.

Created in p5.js

metadata.name: Inertial Packing 001 | Studies Series #4
metadata.description:
Inertial Packing 001 ('IP.001') is the first in a new 'Studies' series exploring technical aspects of larger projects.

IP.001 includes multiple constraint systems, based on Verlet and Euler Integration approaches. Numerous user controls are included:

Interaction:

Mouse/Trackpad:
drag -> camera rotation
drag + CMD/CTR -> camera pan
scroll wheel/pinch -> camera zoom

Key Input:
-, +: reduce | increase  Node Count
{, }: reduce | increase  Packing Dimension
c, v: reduce | increase  Node Adhesion
h, j: reduce | increase  Node Jitter
b, n: disable| enable    Node-Node Collision
z, x: reduce | increase  Stick Constraint
a, s: hide   | show      Nodes
q, w: hide   | show      Wireframe
p: screen capture

Tip:
1. There are 8 unique geometries, should you be inclined to collect a full set.
2. Bringing values outside of "rational" range is encouraged.

Note:
Please post your favorite IP.001 screen captures
TW: @iragreenberg
IG: @greenberg.ira

Built with Three.js, PByte.js, TypeScript, Node

metadata.name: -oO- #30
metadata.description:
The full name is ordered Order, because I feel it's very orderly and I plan on making a Chaos version after. I recently saw an exhibition called Geometric Opulence and I feel this is also a fitting description of this NFT. Made up of points, lines, ellipses, arcs, rectangles, triangles or letters. Colors can be shrill or muted or grayscale. 

Press 'C' to change some Variables and get a new output.
Press 'R' to start/stop a loop of changes. This can run fast that's why I put the epileptic trigger warning.
Press 'S' or click the Mouse button/tap the screen to save a Jaypeg at the full Resolution.

Reserves are for Colorfall holders. Top 5 get 3 spots.

Made with p5js. Hope you like it.

metadata.name: Outside your Window #58
metadata.description:
Never take for granted that we sit in the safety of our homes, behind our windows, sheltered from the elements outside. 

The characteristics of the rain outside the window, and the window itself, will be determined by the mint hash. However, the background color of this piece will constantly change based on the hour of day it is loaded, hence note that the thumbnail will only technically be accurate 1/24 hours out of the day as it represents a static snapshot taken at the time of token rendering.

100% of the primary proceeds will be donated towards flood relief efforts for the devastating December 2021 floods in Malaysia.

Made in p5js
Created December 2021
Artist: @Yazid

metadata.name: Cradle #173
metadata.description:
Billions of years old, ancient remains decay across our Solar System. Mere transient visitors to our star, their ephemeral presence on our worlds is embodied in their creations. In the shadow of their megalithic constructions, we wonder what they might have brought to us.

They brought life.

----

Live mode controls:
'r' - change resolution
's' - save PNG
'f' - render at full speed
'space' - stop/continue rendering

The image quality gradually improves over time. The rendering speed is reduced by default - press 'f' for the maximum speed.

Rendering may be GPU intensive.

metadata.name: lightscapes//linescapes//darkscapes #34
metadata.description:
A landscape made of monochromatic rows arranged by color to create an illusion of depth.

Each token comes with some fixed constraints, some constantly changing elements, and 3 possible styles.

The lightscape mode creates the most natural view, while the darkscape mode reveals the skeleton of the image. The linescape mode blends the two and looks a bit more like an illustration.

CONTROLS:
- click/tap on the image to regenerate and cycle through the different styles
- press 's' to download a png at the current resolution

Hope you like it,
Cino

metadata.name: Lost Twins #332
metadata.description:
Individually, the mints of this token are very simple. Each mint generates half of two cube forms, and each half is assigned random hues (in multiples of 10, from 0 to 360). Collectively as a project, this token challenges the approach of looking for "rarities" in a new way. How the cubes are rendered leaves the possibility for multiple mints to potentially join up on the sides with colors that perfect match each other. Will you find your lost twin?

Made in p5js
Created November 2021
Artist: @Yazid
